# Project Context Discovery (PCD)

Before starting any non-trivial task, read the host project's documentation. This is what makes the boilerplate adapt to whatever repo it lands in.

## What to read (in priority order)

1. **`README.md`** at repo root — primary project description, conventions, commands.
2. **Other root `*.md` files** — `CONTRIBUTING.md`, `ARCHITECTURE.md`, `STYLEGUIDE.md`, etc.
   - **Skip**: `AGENTS.md`, `LICENSE`, `CHANGELOG.md` (these are boilerplate or noise).
3. **`docs/` folder** — design docs, ADRs, API references. Read up to 3 levels deep, markdown / rst / adoc files.

## Token budget

| Task complexity | Max PCD files | Max PCD tokens |
|---|---|---|
| Trivial (single line, typo) | 0 | 0 |
| Simple (single file edit) | 1–2 | ~3K |
| Standard (feature, bug fix) | 3–5 | ~6K |
| Complex (architecture, refactor) | up to 8 | ~10K |

If a project doc set is huge, prioritize: (a) section that names the area you're working in, (b) overall architecture / structure, (c) coding conventions.

## Priority hierarchy

1. **Boilerplate structural rules** — delegation playbook, git safety, file ownership — never overridden.
2. **Project-specific conventions** — naming, architecture, style, test patterns — override boilerplate coding defaults.
3. **Boilerplate coding defaults** (skills) — apply only where the project has no opinion.

## When to skip PCD

- Trivial fixes (typo, single line).
- Pure read-only research where the question doesn't depend on conventions.
- Continuations of a previous task in the same session where context is already loaded.

## When delegating

When you delegate to a subagent, include the relevant project context paths in the task description so the subagent doesn't re-discover from scratch. Example: `Project context: README.md (Setup section), docs/api-conventions.md`.
